{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/syphilis/background-information/definition/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"d6720e54-e02c-58ce-b1a6-033c00e802a7","slug":"definition","fullItemName":"Definition","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field b50db302-9245-4082-a949-e88b831834f5 --><h2>What is it?</h2><!-- end field b50db302-9245-4082-a949-e88b831834f5 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 5fc4165d-1e40-4fff-bd78-767b9b8bb4cf --><!-- begin field 98d10084-a0fc-48fb-9cf6-81c38def4a2e --><ul><li><strong>Syphilis is an infectious disease caused by the spirochete bacterium <em>Treponema pallidum</em> </strong>— untreated infection can persist for years and result in severe cardiovascular, ocular and neurological <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/syphilis/background-information/complications/\">complications</a>. </li><li><strong>Most cases are sexually transmitted during direct contact with an infectious lesion </strong>(usually involving the genital, rectal, or oral mucous surfaces).<ul><li><em>T. pallidum</em> invades through mucous membranes or abraded skin at the point of contact with an infectious lesion. The spirochetes multiply locally and then disseminate though the bloodstream and lymphatics.</li><li>The incubation period is around 21 days but can range from 9 to 90 days depending on the infectious dose.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Transmission can also occur:</strong><ul><li>Vertically from mother to child during pregnancy — serological screening for syphilis is part of routine antenatal care in the UK.</li><li>Through sharing of needles in injecting drug users.</li><li>More rarely, through blood products or organ transplant — screening of donations is mandatory in the UK.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Early syphilis</strong> (defined as the first 2 years after infection) includes 3 stages:<ul><li><a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/syphilis/diagnosis/when-to-suspect-syphilis/#primary-syphilis\">Primary syphilis</a> — characterized by a painless ulcer (chancre) at the site of infection (most commonly the genital area) and local lymphadenopathy.</li><li><a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/syphilis/diagnosis/when-to-suspect-syphilis/#secondary-syphilis\">Secondary syphilis</a> — systemic involvement which can present with a wide range of clinical features including:<ul><li>Skin and hair changes such as a maculopapular rash, condylomata lata (moist wart-like lesions) and patchy alopecia.</li><li>Oral lesions ('snail tract lesions').</li><li>Generalized lymphadenopathy.</li><li>Low-grade fever, headache, and malaise.</li></ul></li><li><a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/syphilis/diagnosis/when-to-suspect-syphilis/#latent-syphilis\">Early latent syphilis</a> — confirmed infection in the absence of any current clinical features.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Late syphilis</strong> (defined as more than 2 years after infection) includes 2 stages:<ul><li><a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/syphilis/diagnosis/when-to-suspect-syphilis/#latent-syphilis\">Late latent syphilis</a> — confirmed infection in the absence of any current clinical features.</li><li><a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/syphilis/diagnosis/when-to-suspect-syphilis/#tertiary-syphilis\">Tertiary syphilis</a> — rare, but may present with cardiac disease (for example aortic aneurysm), cutaneous disease (for example gummatous lesions), and/or neurological disease (for example tabes dorsalis, and general paresis).</li></ul></li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/syphilis/references/\">IUSTI, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/syphilis/references/\">CDC, 2015a</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/syphilis/references/\">Kingston, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/syphilis/references/\">Stoltey, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/syphilis/references/\">WHO, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/syphilis/references/\">Peeling, 2017</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/syphilis/references/\">Thakrar, 2018</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/syphilis/references/\">BASHH, 2019</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/syphilis/references/\">ECDC, 2019</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/syphilis/references/\">PHE, 2019</a>]</p><!-- end field 98d10084-a0fc-48fb-9cf6-81c38def4a2e --><!-- end item 5fc4165d-1e40-4fff-bd78-767b9b8bb4cf -->","topic":{"id":"e20bf9b2-b7e3-5fd7-8829-79eff4ba17c6","topicId":"acdacd5c-088e-4bc3-b3f7-ec4a5cdf69d3","topicName":"Syphilis","slug":"syphilis","lastRevised":"Last revised in December 2019","chapters":[{"id":"e937b36a-5802-56e1-8c33-d31a18aa8993","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"8e1009a7-fe76-55c5-a3b4-71f4ab22bd6e","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"3744efb5-ed9a-556d-b9ca-9497279f7760","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"1a6d6164-e61e-5a2b-899c-b42fdd49c070","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"42b3bae7-13c9-5f24-8610-e6373d51db6c","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"783939a0-7dd0-51dc-b0f1-1a79adaeeca2","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","subChapters":[{"id":"481c647b-0185-5ec1-944f-ea3f095a698e","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"5d1c604c-5520-5fd3-906b-277d5bc648e4","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Ou